at nineteenth-century reform acts against religious monopoly were aspects of this process of political organization. While religion did not disappear, these political actions gradually changed the constitutional position of religion.As a result, a political vacuum was created which was then filled by a secular "clerisy". These "fit and proper persons", educated in the reformed universities, qualified by success in competitive examinations, began to fill positions in the Civil Service and in the professions. The effect was to replace the eighteenth-century system of confessional loyalties with a liberal political culture based on merit. Lubenow's latest study examines the work of these intertwining nineteenth-century secular-liberal processes. Steeped deeply in archival research, this book considers biographical characteristics such as education, political connections and social associations, but it is equally conceptually guided by categories such as liberalism and secularism. It fills an important gap in the political history of nineteenth-century British liberalism by taking up the question of entanglement of secularity and liberality in the foundation of the modern state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aModern History. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAlgernon West.  aArthur Balfour.  aCharles Trevelyan.  aChartists.  aIndian mutiny.  aJohn Morley.  aMaynard Keynes.  aNapoleon.  aNorthcote-Trevelyan Report.  aPeterloo.  aReginald Welby.  aRobert Lowes Order in Council.  aRoman Catholic Emancipation.  aStafford Northcote.  aTest Acts.  aThomas Babington Macaulay.  aWilliam Anson.  aWilliam Gladstone.  acomparative biography.  aprosopography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2024z9